Ben Jonson is constantly mentioned by them as one whose work is in striking contrast to that of Shakespeare, and Mrs. Pott could hardly find a single line in his work to parallel any of the Pramus entries. Well, let readers judge for themselves. The work of Ben Jonson is that of a man who was steeped to the lips in classical authors; consequently we shall find him repeating the learning of Bacon with a literalism that is al- most painfully different from Shakespeare‚ whose knowledge of the classics was derived almost entirely through English channels. Once or twice only does Shakespeare happen to bring into his plays Latin tags noted by Bacon, although they can be found by the score in others; but in Ben Jonson they abound, and not unfrequently in a context that is manifestly stolen from Bacon.

There is no evidence to prove conclusively that Bacon and Shakespeare ever met, or were acquainted with each other. But the case of Ben Jonson is dif- ferent. Jonson at one time acted as a kind of secretary to Bacon, and translated, or assisted to translate, his essays into Latin.
